          "rationale": "Texas law requires a person who prepares or serves food (including a catering operation) to hold a food establishment permit. The state DSHS permit under Tex. Health & Safety Code 437.0055 is the residual permit that applies where no county or public health district issues one, renewed every two years; in most cities and counties the operative permit is the LOCAL city/county/public-health-district food permit, which is often renewed annually (437.008). Check your local health department.",
          "userAction": "Ask this caterer for its current food establishment permit (from the local health department where one exists, otherwise the Texas DSHS permit).",
          "notes": "DELIBERATE BROADENING (recorded): the statutory 437.0055 trigger is the residual no-local-authority case, but this rule fires for every food-preparing caterer because SOME food permit (local-first, DSHS residual) is required either way - the rationale/userAction carry the local-first structure (UNVER-37). No periodMonths: the DSHS permit is 2-year but the (more common) local permit is often ANNUAL, so a projected term for a no-expiry document would overstate currency - the printed expiry governs; a permit with no readable expiry reads NeedsDocumentInfo (CONF-13)."
        }
      ]
